{"created":"2015-05-15T02:15:33+00:00","modified":"2015-06-26T18:29:56+00:00","valid":{"from":"2013-10-30T21:51:43+00:00","to":"3013-10-30T21:51:43+00:00"},"hreflang":"en","guid":"76230881-322d-4c39-88b3-514bee1fd4b6","byline":"Kai Ryssdal","itags":["76230881322dc3998b3a514bee1fd4b6","Marketplace","Marketplace for Wednesday, October 30, 2013","PMP:Marketplace_PMP"],"published":"2013-10-30T21:51:43+00:00","teaser":"What's it take to scare people these days?","contenttemplated":"[{\"type\":\"text/html\",\"content\":\"<p>For all the kids out there waiting in fevered anticipation of all the candy they&apos;re gonna get tomorrow night, there&apos;s a not-small contingent of adults who are a bit glum. Halloween is, of course, the end of the scare season. That&apos;s bad news for the small business people who own and operate haunted houses. And it turns out the business of boo is surprisingly complicated. Time magazine&apos;s <a href=\\\"http://entertainment.time.com/author/rothmanlily/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Lily Rothman</a> has <a href=\\\"http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,2155000,00.html\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">penned a story</a> for the latest issue of the magazine called <a href=\\\"http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,2155000,00.html?pcd=pw-edit\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">&quot;Monsters Inc: Inside the weird world of professional haunting.&quot;</a> She says haunted houses have had to up the ante to get a gasp these days, including one in Pennsylvania:</p>\"},{\"content\":\"<p>&quot;The idea was to get that adrenaline rush for people who have been to a lot of haunted houses -- you would have the option to go through the haunted house naked.&quot;</p>\",\"type\":\"text/html\"},{\"type\":\"text/html\",\"content\":\"<p><object classid=\\\"clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000\\\" codebase=\\\"http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=9,0,47,0\\\" id=\\\"flashObj\\\"><param name=\\\"movie\\\" v